1	\chapter{Uniform Mordell--Lang bounds}
2	\label{chap:main}
3	
4	% archon:covers MR4276287UniformityInMordellLangForCurves.lean
5	
6	This chapter derives the uniform bounds on rational points and torsion packets
7	from the geometric and height estimates established earlier.
8	
9	\section{External inputs}
10	
11	\begin{lemma}[Northcott's theorem]
12	  \label{lem:northcott}
13	  \lean{MR4276287UniformityInMordellLangForCurves.northcott}
14	  \uses{def:ambient_setup}
15	  \textit{Source: standard (see, e.g., Hindry--Silverman, Theorem B.2.3; possibly Mathlib.NumberTheory.Heights).}
16	  For any number field \(K\), any positive integer \(D\), and any bound \(B\),
17	  there are only finitely many \(\overline{\mathbb{Q}}\)-points of a projective variety
18	  that have degree \(\le D\) over \(K\) and Weil height \(\le B\).
19	\end{lemma}
20	
21	% SOURCE QUOTE PROOF: "By Northcott's Theorem implies that $\tau(s)$ comes from a finite set in $\mathbb{A}_{g}(\IQbar)$ that depends only on $g,d,$ and $\ell$." (read from references/MR4276287-mordell-lang-curves-source/RatPt.tex)
22	\begin{proof}
23	  Standard finiteness result: the number of algebraic integers of bounded degree
24	  and size is finite by the product formula. See Hindry--Silverman, Theorem B.2.3.
25	  The relevant instance here is applied to the moduli point \(\tau(s)\) in
26	  \(\mathbb{A}_{g,\ell}(\IQbar)\) viewed as a projective variety.
27	\end{proof}
